<h1>From Major General Philip Schuyler</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear General.</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Fort George [N.Y.] April 12th: 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Yesterday I had the Honor to receive your Favor of the 3d Instant by Bennet, who overtook me on my Way to this placeAll is in readiness to move as soon as the Lakes open, which I
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0055">[55]</span>
hope will be in a Day or twoGeneral Thomas is here6 Companies of Burrels Regiment from Connecticut two Companies of the first pennsylvania Batallion three of the New Jersey; the Remainder of these Corps are gone on, whereof two Companies are about 45 Miles below Crown point, the rest have reached CanadaWe have also here two Companies of Van Schaicks of this Colony; and five Companies of the second pennsylvania Battalion are at Fort Edward waiting for the Lake to open, as I have no Quarters for them at this placeThe Remainder of Van Schaicks are not yet raised, and two Companies of the first pennsylvania Battalion are on their Way from New York.</p>
<p>I should be extremely happy my dear General to pay my Devoirs to you At New York, but I do not see a possibility of quitting this Quarter, without risking all in Canada: unless some other General Officer should relieve me, I shall therefore presume to remain until I receive your farther Orders.</p>
<p>4 OClock <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">P.M.</span> This Moment the post from Canada is arrivedInclose you Copies of all the papers I received. The Intelligence they afford is so alarming that I beg Leave to repeat my Wish that a considerable Body of Troops should be immediately sent up.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I have stopped the Courier at this place, and he goes back immediately to advise our Friends in Canada that the Troops now here will soon be in Canada, and I have presumed to add that they will be followed by three or four thousand more This Intelligence<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> will keep up their Spirits and intimidate our Enemies.</p>
<p>I have heretofore observed to your Excellency that I had never received a Return of the Army in Canada I am on that account still incapable of letting you know the Strength of our Army there; I am equally in the Dark with Respect to the Arrangement made in Officering the two Regiments that were to be raised out of the Troops that wintered there.</p>
<p>The provisions at these posts is very trifling. None of what General Lee has contracted for is come to Albany, and unless a speedy Supply is sent up our Troops in Canada must sufferI have written on this Subject to General Thompson before I left Albany, and altho I make not the least Doubt but that he will forward it if he can, yet I beg Leave to mention it least he
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0056">[56]</span>
should forget to mention it on the Arrival of his superior officer at New York.</p>
<p>I am seized with a copious scorbutic Eruption, which I have frequently experienced and imagined that it threw off some other more disagreeable DisorderI believe it will not confine me or prevent me from doing my Duty I am Dear General most sincerely Your obedient humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Ph: Schuyler</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0042-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ New York Public Library, New York ]">NN</span>: Schuyler Papers.
 Schuyler sent this letter unsealed to New York with a covering letter to Gen. William Thompson requesting Thompson to seal GWs letter after perusing it and to forward it to him by Express wherever he may be (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). GW received the letter at New York on 18 April (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0073" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 19 April 1776</a>).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Schuyler enclosed copies of letters written to him from Montreal by David Wooster on 16 Mar. and Moses Hazen on 1 April, two private letters to Capt. William Goforth at Trois Rivires from Capt. Gershom Mott and adjutant John Brogdon, both dated 26 Mar. at Quebec, and an extract of an unidentified letter from Goforth. (All of these documents are in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.) Mott and Brogdon report a skirmish near Quebec between some American troops and a small force of French Canadians who recently had been rallied to the royal standard by a few Roman Catholic priests and British regulars. Although the Americans were victorious in this instance, Hazen viewed the event with foreboding. The Canadians taking up Arms so early against us, he wrote Schuyler, is of the most important consequence, we have brot about ourselves by Mismanagement what Governor Carlton himself could never effect. Much of the local populace, Hazen thought, had been alienated by the American failure to take Quebec, the general weakness of the Continental army in Canada, the neglect of parish priests, the lack of hard cash to pay for supplies, and the misbehavior of American troops, who, according to both Hazens and Goforths accounts, sometimes took what they needed or wanted at the point of a bayonet. Hazen and Goforth also report various rumors of impending Indian attacks. Wooster sent Schuyler intelligence of some Mischief contriving by the Kings Troops and the Inhabitants Traders and Savages in &amp; about Detroit and reminded him in general terms of the shortage of men, money, gunpowder, and provisions in Canada.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0042-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The words I hope appear here in the letter-book copy.</p>

</div>
